{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Verifier-first closure\n\nThe verifier \u2014 not your judgment, not your reading of the diff \u2014 decides whether a task is done. Each step below has one product, and the step is finished only when its product exists. A description of intended work is not a product.\n\n## 1. Read\n\nIn a batched call, read everything the project puts in front of you: the task description, the surrounding instructions, any acceptance criteria, the verifier or test files that define pass, and the files the task names. Read parallel independent slices in one round.\n\nStop reading when you can name three things:\n\n1. The deliverable \u2014 what artifact you must produce.\n2. The path \u2014 where it must land.\n3. The pass signal \u2014 what observable result the verifier emits when the deliverable is correct.\n\nIf a notes directory at `/workspace/learned/` exists from earlier work, read it first. Prior corrections about defect categories or recurring failures save more time than they take.\n\n## 2. Contract\n\nIn one line, write down the three things from step 1: deliverable, exact path, observable pass signal. This is the finish line. You cannot aim for a finish line you have not written down.\n\n## 3. Build\n\nWrite the smallest implementation that satisfies the contract. Match the local style by reading one or two nearby files of the same kind. No drive-by refactors, no helpers used only once, no defensive branches the contract does not promise.\n\nHonour implied invariants \u2014 bounds, edge values, concurrency safety, cleanup of anything that accumulates, idempotence on re-run \u2014 whether the task spells them out or not. When a change touches values at the edge of a range, decide explicitly which side is included; conventions are rarely symmetric, so picking by feel introduces a quiet defect. When the work involves concurrency, async cancellation, or shared state, ensure the cancellation, cleanup, and idempotence paths exist alongside the happy path.\n\nFor code that consumes external input \u2014 text files, structured records, log streams \u2014 handle the empty case, the duplicate case, the malformed case, and the boundary-of-the-window case.\n\nIf your notes record a fix for a similar shape from prior work, apply that fix at the start rather than rediscovering it.\n\n## 4. Verify\n\nRun the verifier or pass-check named in step 2. Read the output to the end, not the exit signal alone. The verifier is the source of truth \u2014 your reading of the diff, your sense that it \"should work\", and the absence of new errors are all provisional until the verifier agrees.\n\nIf the verifier fails, identify the root cause, not the surface symptom. The same symptom returns until the root cause is fixed. Re-enter step 3 with the diagnosis sharpened \u2014 change the diagnosis, not the punctuation, before a second full patch cycle.\n\nIf multiple checks exist, run them all. Passing one while breaking another is no progress.\n\n## 5. Close\n\nConfirm the deliverable is at the path the contract named, the verifier produces the pass signal the contract named, and any artifacts the task asked for are visible to the next process that reads the working area. If a contract row has no satisfying artifact, the task is not done; return to step 3 for that row.\n\n## Persistent notes\n\nIf `/workspace/learned/` exists and is writable, keep it tight:\n\n- `PATTERNS.md` \u2014 short rules that have proven useful on similar work. One line each, one situation per line.\n- `DEFECTS.md` \u2014 categories of defect encountered and the corrected approach. Format: `<category> | <symptom> | <correction>`. One line per category.\n- `INDEX.md` \u2014 top patterns currently in heavy rotation, promoted only after repeated success.\n\nHabits:\n\n1. Write a line the moment a surprise lands \u2014 deferring loses it.\n2. Only entries with verified outcomes go in. An unverified line corrupts whoever reads next.\n3. Update lines in place; do not duplicate.\n4. When current observation contradicts a stored line, replace it.\n5. Skip language-generic knowledge, today's identifier, today's path \u2014 anything reproducible from version control.\n\nWhen a task begins, scan these files; if the current task smells like a recurrence \u2014 same defect category, same shape \u2014 start from the recorded correction rather than from scratch.\n\n## Tool budget\n\nBatch independent probes in one round. Serialize writes per surface \u2014 one write, then re-inspect, then the next. Concurrent writes are difficult to disentangle on failure.\n\nNear a deadline, ship the smallest finished slice that satisfies the verifier \u2014 partial proof beats endless intake. A landed verifier-green change beats an elegant draft that did not get committed in time.\n\n## Exit\n\nSteps complete for the named deliverable, every contract row honoured, the verifier green \u2014 stop. Action ended is progress; another paragraph is not.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}